Hello CD, as we approach the end of the off-season, we are making our final preparations for the new season. I have a question that has been on my mind. What type of filament do you use when building your robot? We have a Bambu Lab A-1 Mini printer, which we‚Äôve been using for about 6-7 months, and so far, we‚Äôve only used PLA and TPU filaments (we managed to get good quality on PLA prints , but I can‚Äôt say the same for TPU, probably because we haven‚Äôt mastered it yet). I‚Äôm curious about which filaments other teams use for 3D printed parts on their robots, and what things they pay attention to. I know that 3D printing technology is very important for FRC, and I want to learn new things. Thanks in advance for your answers.

TPU has to be dry to print well. Even when I got OK prints on TPU, they improved noticeably with the filament dryer.

PLA or PLA-plus are good for most of what we do (mounts, shields, etc.) We haven‚Äôt gone into any more exotic materials as that‚Äôs not what‚Äôs remotely limiting factor for our program.

We have had very good luck with PETG. It is very durable, not quite as brittle or stiff as PLA and very easy to print with. Very good bed adhesion particularly on the textured Bambu bed and Majigoo or other bed adhesive/release agent. We make some snap-on covers for swerve modules and clips/spacers for shafts etc with PETG where the slight flex is a huge benefit and much easier to print than very flexy TPU on a Bambu. There is a new formulation on the Bambu site, PETG-HF, which we don‚Äôt have much experience with but seems very similar to the prior PETG from the few offseason prints we have done. And PETG comes in lime green, which is very important‚Ä¶

95% of our prints are Bambu PLA Matte. With proper print settings and design it works fine almost everywhere we want to use printed parts, including pulleys, gears, and spacers.

We have occasionally used Prusament PCCF and Bambu TPU (haven‚Äôt tried TPU HF). Historically we used Duramic PLA Plus, and there is still some in the shop.

We have 2 prusa mk3s and 1 mark one. Some mentors and students have printers we also use on occasion. We use regular pla for awards or art stuff (team logos, name tags, etc). We use petg for non load bearing spacers. We use pc-cf and onyx for load bearing parts (basically pivots with spine xl). We tend to print gears in petg, then upgrade to pccf, then to metal if needed after each failure.

I heard good things about pla+. We haven‚Äôt used it but heard it‚Äôs pretty good for most applications.

I use a mix of sources, most of them PETG because it‚Äôs South Carolina and it gets hot.

GreenGate3D deals in recycled PETG, and their quality has been immaculate in roll after roll. It is not the cheap stuff, but it is the GOOD stuff. This year‚Äôs SCRAP trophies were run with a mix of Black, Bubblegum, and Spearmint. They put a voucher in your team‚Äôs dashboard this year to cover half a spool. Use it and thank me later.

IMG_40491920√ó1440 191 KB

Protopasta makes a lot of interesting artisanal stuff. They also use a lot of their production waste to make a pretty useful recycled PLA (and there‚Äôs now a recycled PETG counterpart I haven‚Äôt sampled). We used it to make spacers, test plates, and even some test gears for an intake that never happened Bought in 6-packs, it comes down to about $15/kg shipped; you can Amazon hunt to get spools cheaper, but if you want a consistent supply at a good price that‚Äôs certainly in the zone. They too have a PDV in your dashboard. Use that too!

IMG_36591920√ó1440 132 KB

Prusament isn‚Äôt cheap stuff either, but I used it to make the SCRIW champion trophy this year and it came out great. (The black is GreenGate3D, because I had it on-hand.)

IMG_55061920√ó1440 308 KB

(The finalist trophies were done in Duramic PETG. I don‚Äôt love it in the age of Bambu speeds; it requires an incredibly slow print speed, though the silver seems to be exceptionally bad as last year‚Äôs champion trophies were done in gold Duramic PETG and I could run them incrementally faster. The strip of white tape on the middle one was covering the names of this year‚Äôs SCRIWDriver Award recipients; much like the in-season Volunteer of the Year award, this is chosen in advance.)

While I‚Äôm not wild about Duramic PETG, Duramic PLA Plus is my preferred ‚ÄúI need to Amazon something now‚Äù solution. Pricing gets weird as Amazon varieties are wont to do, but they have a great variety of colors. I‚Äôve also got some Elegoo Rapid PETG that I need to audition in my printer but which comes highly recommended.

I have only dipped my toe into the TPU waters; Polymaker and Overture have both been fine.

While most filaments benefit from it, PETG and TPU will particularly benefit from a session in a filament dryer. I use this cheap EIBOS unit. When not in my AMS, my filament lives in 47-quart gasketed totes that seal well and hold 10 spools each. I made a printed riser that goes in the bottom so you can dump in desiccant and not have it getting all in the spools.
